05033nam a22007335i 9780813563480DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2013027196  a97808135634807 a10.36019/97808135634802doi  a(DE-B1597)529785  a(OCoLC)889814072  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aBT707b.J46 2014 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a261.8/35892231 aJenkins, Kathleen E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSacred Divorce :bReligion, Therapeutic Culture, and Ending Life Partnerships /cKathleen E. Jenkins. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (250 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Social Shame and Religious Tools -- t2. Divorce Work as Cultural Strategy -- t3. Solitary Work through Community -- t4. Cautious Clergy -- t5. Rich Lived Practice -- t6. Religious Emotion and Multiple Family Forms -- tAppendix on Methods -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEven in our world of redefined life partnerships and living arrangements, most marriages begin through sacred ritual connected to a religious tradition. But if marriage rituals affirm deeply held religious and secular values in the presence of clergy, family, and community, where does divorce, which severs so many of these sacred bonds, fit in? Sociologist Kathleen Jenkins takes up this question in a work that offers both a broad, analytical perspective and a uniquely intimate view of the role of religion in ending marriages. For more than five years, Jenkins observed religious support groups and workshops for the divorced and interviewed religious practitioners in the midst of divorces, along with clergy members who advised them. Her findings appear here in the form of eloquent and revealing stories about individuals managing emotions in ways that make divorce a meaningful, even sacred process. Clergy from mainline Protestant denominations to Baptist churches, Jewish congregations, Unitarian fellowships, and Catholic parishes talk about the concealed nature of divorce in their congregations. Sacred Divorce describes their cautious attempts to overcome such barriers, and to assemble meaningful symbols and practices for members by becoming compassionate listeners, delivering careful sermons, refitting existing practices like Catholic annulments and Jewish divorce documents (gets), and constructing new rituals. With attention to religious, ethnic, and class variations, covering age groups from early thirties to mid-sixties and separations of only a few months to up to twenty years, Sacred Divorce offers remarkable insight into individual and cultural responses to divorce and the social emotions and spiritual strategies that the clergy and the faithful employ to find meaning in the breach. At once a sociological document, an ethnographic analysis, and testament of personal experience, Sacred Divorce provides guidance, strategies and answers to readers looking for answers and those looking to heal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDivorcexRelgious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aDivorcexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aDivorcexReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aDivorcezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acultural respones to divorce.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356348040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813563480423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813563480.jpg  a978-3-11-066615